GPU Growth Over Time

Introduction

The primary purpose of this project is to guide you through the entire data science pipeline. We have chosen to analyze how a GPU's release date and specifications impact its manufacturer's suggested retail price (MSRP). By doing so, we aim to capture the relationship between the release date, specifications, and price of GPUs to predict future GPU specifications based on their release date and price. This ensures that buyers get a fair deal and allows us to visualize the overall trend of price-to-performance over time.

Why are GPUs so important? GPU stands for graphics processing unit, and it is hardware designed to handle large amounts of parallel processing. This makes it essential for tasks requiring intensive computational power, such as rendering complex graphics, machine learning, and scientific simulations. GPUs are critical to individual consumers for gaming, video editing, content creation, and companies utilizing their power for machine learning and deep learning. By analyzing and predicting the future prices of GPUS as well as how powerful they may become, it allows people to see if a new line of GPUs fits the general price-to-performance trend and, from that, make the decision to wait for prices to go down, buy an older generation GPU, or wait for the next generation depending on their needs. Choosing a cost-effective GPU is essential for larger companies requiring hundreds to tens of thousands of GPUs and general consumers.

TechPowerUp limits the amount of information it displays in its tables, so to get all the data that we needed, we sorted the GPU data by year of release and scrapped the HTTP tables that contained the product name, GPU chip, release date, bus, memory, GPU clock, memory clock, and shader, TMU, and ROP cores. The GPU chip is the name of the physical chip in the GPU. The bus refers to the type and speed of the interface through which the GPU communicates with the rest of the system. The memory contains information about the amount, type, and width of the data path between the GPU and the VRAM in the card. The GPU clock is the speed at which the GPU's processor core operates. It's usually measured in megahertz (MHz) or gigahertz (GHz). The GPU clock speed determines how quickly the GPU can process data and execute instructions. The memory clock is the speed at which the memory on the graphics card operates. Finally, the shader, TMU, and ROP cores number the amount of Shader cores, Texture Mapping Units (TMUs), and Raster Operations Pipelines (ROPs). Shader cores are responsible for executing programmable shaders, which are small programs that process vertices and pixels in 3D graphics rendering. TMUs are accountable for applying textures to 3D objects during rendering. ROPs are responsible for the final stage of the rendering pipeline, where the pixels are processed before being written to the frame buffer.

The scraping works for individual years, but due to the website's anti-DDOS attack features prevent rapid or continuous requests for various web pages. This prevents the loop in the code from working correctly, so we scrapped each year separately and compiled them together.

In[]:
# we will scrap the data from 2004 to 2024
# since we already scrapped the data from 2024, 
# we will stop at 2023
end = 2024 + 1      # make it inclusive
start = 2004 - 1    # make it inclusive

for year in range(end, start, -1):
    # prevent the website from triggering DDOS Alert
    time.sleep(60)
    
    url = 'https://www.techpowerup.com/gpu-specs/?released={year}&workstation=No&igp=No&sort=name'
    html = requests.get(url).content
    soup = BeautifulSoup(html, 'html.parser')
    table = soup.find("table", class_="processors")

    columnsData = table.findAll("tr")
    
    for row in columnsData:
        rowsData = row.findAll("td")
        print(rowsData)
        if(len(rowsData) == num):
            df.loc[len(df)] = [data.text for data in rowsData]

After we scrape the initial data from TechPowerUp, we need to add the release MSPR. TechPowerUp has this information, but it is not presented in the tables. Instead, it is listed on the individual web pages of the GPUs. We manually scrapped each initial price for the GPUs when available.

We needed to adjust the MSRP for inflation. To do this, we accessed this inflation API (https://www.statbureau.org) from StatBeauru. We set it so the adjusted release price would be in May 2024 USD.

In[]:
# https://www.statbureau.org
# Using APIs to get the inflation USD price (convert to 05/01/2024)
def calculate_inflation_price(start_date, end_date, start_price):
    url = 'https://www.statbureau.org/calculate-inflation-price-jsonp?jsoncallback=?'
    params = {
        'country': 'united-states',
        'start': start_date,
        'end': end_date,
        'amount': start_price,
        'format': True
    }

    response = requests.get(url, params=params)
    data = response.text
    
    # delete all the non-integer characters in the str,
    # so it can be converted to a float variable later
    end_price = re.sub(r'[^0-9.]', '', data)
    return float(end_price)

# MSRP adjusted to the inflated price to 2024/05/01
df["Inflation MSRP"] = np.nan
end_date = "2024/5/1"

for i in range(len(df)):
    df.loc[i, "Inflation MSRP"] = calculate_inflation_price(df.loc[i, "Released Date"].strftime('%Y/%m/%d'), end_date, df.loc[i, "MSRP"])

df.drop('MSRP', axis=1, inplace=True)
df.head(10)

For the shader, TMU, and ROP cores, we noticed that some of the older GPUs had four numbers instead of 3; upon further investigation, that was because they had two types of shader cores. We chose to make the shader core number for those GPUs a combination of those sub-shader cores.

In[]:
# Spliting Shaders/TMUs/ROPs into three different columns
df["Shaders"] = 0
df["TMUs"] = 0
df["ROPs"] = 0

for i in range(len(df)):
    s = df.loc[i, "Shaders / TMUs / ROPs"].replace("/", "")
    all_results = s.split()
    
    temp = 0
    if len(all_results) == 4:
        temp = int(all_results.pop(0))
    
    df.loc[i, "Shaders"] = int(all_results[0]) + temp
    df.loc[i, "TMUs"] = int(all_results[1])
    df.loc[i, "ROPs"] = int(all_results[2])

df.drop('Shaders / TMUs / ROPs', axis=1, inplace=True)

For the GPU memory feature, we have to convert the unit from MB to GB (1 GB = 1000 MB), and store those values as integers.

In[]:
# Creating a new column for Memory, and coverting the unit to MB
df["Memory (in MB)"] = 0

for i in range(len(df)):
    s = df.loc[i, "Memory"]
    
    result = re.match(r'(\d+) ((MB)|(GB))', s)
    
    df.loc[i, "Memory (in MB)"] = int(result[1])
    
    if result[2] == 'GB':
        df.loc[i, "Memory (in MB)"] *= 1000

df.drop('Memory', axis=1, inplace=True)

    df.loc[i, "Memory Clock (in MHz)"] = int(df.loc[i, "Memory clock"].replace(" MHz", ""))

The data we collected so far is useful. However, not all of it is needed and just clutters up the data frame. Here are the data sets we deemed unnecessary and why:

  • GPU chip: This is just the name of the chipset on the card. It has no impact on the actual performance.

  • GPU Bus: This dictates the type and speed of the connection between the GPU and the rest of the system. It usually follows a standard set at the time and changes only after many years. These changes are generally architectural changes that are hard to quantify, and we deem them not significant enough to include.

  • Memory amount, type, and bus: Similar to the GPU bus, the memory type changes only when the standard for memory changes in architecture. The memory bus also does not have much of an impact. We removed the memory amount as while it does impact price and change throughout the years, it's at inconsistent rates and often stays at a level for long periods of time.

In[]:
# Delete GPU Chip and Bus columns
df.drop('GPU Chip', axis=1, inplace=True)
df.drop('Bus', axis=1, inplace=True)

# Training data (X, y), T time steps, alpha step
def grad_descent(X, y, T, alpha):
    m, n = X.shape              # m = #examples, n = #features
    theta = np.zeros((n, 1))    # initialize parameters
    f = np.zeros(T)             # track loss over time

    for i in range(T):
        # loss for current parameter vector theta
        f[i] = 0.5* np.linalg.norm(X.dot(theta) - y)**2
        # compute steepest ascent at f(theta)
        g = np.transpose(X).dot(X.dot(theta) - y)
        # step down the gradient
        theta = theta - alpha * g
    return theta, f

Interpretation: Insight & Policy Decision

Looking at our linear regression models for all of the features, we could predict the various specifications of a GPU using release price and date with moderate success. The predicted features of the GPUs averaged between 0.34 and 0.66 standard deviations away from the actual values. An average error of 0.34 standard deviations is mostly accurate. This would equate to a prediction where only 26.61% of data points would fall into a 0.34 standard deviation range if the data followed a normal distribution. However, the 0.66 standard deviations would equate to 49.07% of the data.

The accuracy of each specification varies as some aspects of a graphics card may not be influenced by price and release date as much. Memory speed is an arbitrarily determined feature, and even cheaper GPUs with the same launch year may have higher memory clocks than more expensive cards. However, an explanation for the error for all the models is that we haven't captured all of the features that influence GPU prices and that GPU prices, their specifications, and release date don't have a linear relationship in real life. Yes, generally GPU specifications increase over time, but the amount they increase every generation and the price that comes with those specifications aren't straightforward. There can be generations of GPUs that generally present lackluster performance boosts, such as with the 20 series Nvidia GPUs, where consumers complained that there was not enough of a performance boost for the higher price compared to the older GPUs. Furthermore, Graphic card companies consider current part availability, demand for graphics cards, and the state of the economy to determine the release price of GPUs. There is no real way to predict those influences, and even if we could, nothing stops people from charging whatever they want for their cards, especially for enterprise cards, where there are few to no alternatives.

All those factors explain why our data contains outliers and why the price and GPU specifications sometimes don't have a clear linear relationship. Moore's Law may also introduce error as it dictates that transistor count growth is exponential. This is more applicable to the older GPUs. However, Moore's law has slowed down dramatically in recent years, and the overall trends found in the data show a linear relationship between date and specifications as we don't take into account the actual transistor count.

What does all this tell us about the trends of GPUs over time? Well according to all of our data You're able to predict GPU specs based on price and release date with moderate success, and while this may not be the best gauge to predict future releases for GPUS, may be able to give an individual a baseline for their expectations.
